answers.body_markdown:
It&#39;s because you&#39;re using the same pattern for the two routes. You try to match two routes with the pattern : `/movies/:parameter`. For every requests, Express try to match the request path with registered urls in the application. With the given example :

```
/movies/Lorem Ipsum # Match the /movies/:title
/movies/Classical # Match the /movies/:title
```

Why ? Because the route `/movies/:title` is the first in the declaration order. The name of the parameter doesn&#39;t count, because when you&#39;re sending your request, express doesn&#39;t know that &quot;Lorem ipsum&quot; is a `title` and &quot;Classical&quot; is a `genre` ! The name of the parameter in the route declaration is only there to call it in your handler with `req.params.title` by example.

# How to fix that ?

Change your pattern, use the query instead (https://expressjs.com/fr/api.html#req.query) ! You can use this form : 

```
GET /movies?genre=Classical
GET /movies?title=Lorem%20Ipsum
``` 

And you will have a route like this :

```
app.get(&#39;/movies&#39;, (req, res) =&gt; {
    if (req.query.title)
         // do title research
    else if (req.query.genre)
         // do genre research

    ...
});
```

Have fun !

