You need to change the order of your conditions - first check if a number is a prime, then odd or even.  

E.g. the following code

    lst = range(10)
    
    def is_prime(n):
        &quot;&quot;&quot;&quot;pre-condition: n is a nonnegative integer
        post-condition: return True if n is prime and False otherwise.&quot;&quot;&quot;
        if n &lt; 2:
             return False;
        if n % 2 == 0:
             return n == 2  # return False
        k = 3
        while k*k &lt;= n:
             if n % k == 0:
                 return False
             k += 2
        return True
    
    def is_even(n):
        return True if n % 2 == 0 else False
    
    for number in lst:
        if is_prime(number):
            print(&quot;{} is prime.&quot;.format(number))
        elif is_even(number):
            print(&quot;{} is even.&quot;.format(number))
        else:
            print(&quot;{} is odd.&quot;.format(number))

yields

    0 is even.
    1 is odd.
    2 is prime.
    3 is prime.
    4 is even.
    5 is prime.
    6 is even.
    7 is prime.
    8 is even.
    9 is odd.

The reason your current program is not working, is because actually print that the number is and odd number for each divisor of the odd number.
Try something like this:

    import math
    
    def printNumbers(lowerBound, upperBound):
        for i in range(lowerBound, upperBound):
            if isPrime(i):
                print(i, &quot;is a prime number&quot;)
            elif i%2==0:
                print(i, &quot;is an even number&quot;)
            else:
                print(i, &quot;is an odd number&quot;)
    
    def isPrime(n):
        if n &lt; 2: return False
        boundToCheck = round(math.sqrt(n))
        for i in range(2,boundToCheck+1): #+1 So upperbound is included
            if n%i == 0:
                return False
        return True

Notice how I put the prime check first, as 2 is a prime number as well. 
To check for prime numbers you also only how to go up to the square root of the number to check. If you want you could put the isPrime function&#39;s code inside of the elif-statement of course.

